      <subsection name="Maximize Performance">
        <p>There are several flags added to validate so you can split out various parts and run multiple Validate executions to speed up the processing. Here is one example of how to 
        split up execution. There are other permutations you could do to improve performance, but this is one example:</p>
        <source>
          my_bundle/
          ├── bundle.xml
          ├── data
          │   ├── data_collection.tab
          │   ├── data_collection.xml
          │   ├── release1
          │   │   ├── file1.tab
          │   │   ├── file1.xml
          │   │   ├── file2.tab
          │   │   └── file2.xml
          │   ├── release2
          │   │   ├── file3.tab
          │   │   ├── file3.xml
          │   │   ├── file4.tab
          │   │   └── file4.xml
          │   └── release3
          │       ├── file5.tab
          │       ├── file5.xml
          │       ├── file6.tab
          │       └── file6.xml
          └── document
              ├── document_collection.tab
              └── document_collection.xml
        </source>
        <p>Here is how you could execute multiple validates to split out the work. <b>Note: Always make sure if you split out execution 
        that you execute Bundle Validation (pds4.bundle rule) and content validation.</b></p>
        <source>
          
# Execute bundle validation but only check bundle/collection validity and ignore the products
validate --skip-product-validation -R pds4.bundle -t my_bundle

# Make sure the labels are valid upon delivery but skip content validation until later since it takes longer
validate --no-check-data -R pds4.label -t my_bundle

# Point at several targets with different validate runs for parallelizing content validation
validate -R pds4.label -t my_bundle/document/*.xml
validate -R pds4.label -t my_bundle/release1/*.xml
validate -R pds4.label -t my_bundle/release2/*.xml
validate -R pds4.label -t my_bundle/release3/*.xml

# Or you could do the same thing with target manifests
validate -R pds4.label --target-manifest documents.txt
validate -R pds4.label --target-manifest release1_data.txt
validate -R pds4.label --target-manifest release2_data.txt
validate -R pds4.label --target-manifest release3_data.txt

        </source>
